result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Kaitlin R. Tempest in court by attorney Debra Van Wormer O'Rourke.   Father of DE K.T. also appears in person w/o counsel.  Sue Mueller and intern Rick S appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  State states appearances and status.  K.T. is requesting the no contact provision be dropped.  State is objecting to modification/explains reasons why.  Court questions where the DE would reside if she's not allowed to return to the home of K.T.  State doesn't know.  K.T. responds.  Court advises he set the current bond conditions but would not have done that had he known at the time that the DE was only 17.  Court grants bond modification as requested and the no contact provision is now removed from the bond condition.  State requests it be changed to "not to engage in any violent or abusive contact in the presence of her younger sibling".
